<!--- <center><h3><A HREF="http://www.cs.berkeley.edu/~culler/tinyos/ttx/">The Third International TinyOS Technology Exchange (TTX III)</A>,<br>February 10th, 2006, Stanford University.</h3></center> --->

<h3>TinyOS Programming Manual</h3>
I've recently written a short book on programming TinyOS. Unlike the tutorials,
which are a brief introduction to get you started, or TEPs, which describe
parts of TinyOS 2.0, <A HREF="pubs/tinyos-programming.pdf">Programming TinyOS</A> digs into nesC and how you can use it to build TinyOS applications. 
Except for a few fictional components in the beginning, almost every concept
has a TinyOS 2.0 implementation as an example. A second version of the text,
co-written with David Gay, will soon be <A HREF="http://www.amazon.com/TinyOS-Programming-Philip-Levis/dp/0521896061/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&s=books&qid=1229638381&sr=8-1">available for purchase</A> in April of 2009. We tried to keep the cost
down by making it softcover and having very tiny royalties. Unfortunately,
though, TinyOS programming is not a blockbuster topic, so the book is
a bit pricier than I'd like. Oh well.

